{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:04:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:04:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2753"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2753"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.66,0.08,0.22,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115769"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2753"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97772"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4457"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115769"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic. She gave birth to her first child three weeks ago and reports \u0027struggling to cope\u0027. Her most recent blood tests are normal. She has no past medical history, takes no medications, and has no allergies. She is a single parent, but her mother moved in after the birth to support her with the new baby.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe describes feeling very down, with a low mood since the birth. She finds she cannot sleep at night, even when the baby is sleeping, and feels tired all day and sometimes feels unable to get up to attend to the baby. Her mother has been making meals for her, but she has lost her appetite and rarely finishes them. She finds herself reading the same page of a parenting book over and over, unable to take in the information. She denies thoughts of harming herself or her baby. She describes the birth as being \u0027traumatic\u0027 but denies flashbacks or increased reactivity. She denies hallucinations, delusions, excessive worrying, or manic episodes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes what she is experiencing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adjustment insomnia","Perinatal depression","Adjustment disorder","Baby Blues","Chronic fatigue syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhat this patient has described to her GP is of serious concern in the postnatal period. It is \u0027normal\u0027 for parents to feel tired, overwhelmed, and emotional after a child enters their life, but it is important for doctors to screen for when these symptoms become more severe and may suggest a condition such as depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to be able to distinguish between the common phenomenon known as \u0027Baby Blues\u0027 and the more serious condition of perinatal depression (PND).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe DSM-5 criteria for \u003Cstrong\u003Eperinatal depression\u003C/strong\u003E requires:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA. Five or more of the following symptoms that have been present for two weeks consistently (every or almost every day) and are a change from previous functioning. (One of these symptoms must be either Depressed mood or Loss of interest/pleasure).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDepressed mood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELoss of interest/pleasure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWeight loss or weight gain or appetite changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInsomnia or hypersomnia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPsychomotor agitation or retardation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFatigue or loss of energy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFeelings of worthlessness or excessive guilt\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProblems with concentration or making decisions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecurrent thoughts of death\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EB. These symptoms cause an impairment in functioning for the individual or clinically significant distress\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC. These symptoms cannot be better explained by another medical condition or by another psychiatric diagnosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom the patient\u0027s reports above, she is experiencing five criteria: (1) depressed mood, (2) appetite changes (loss of appetite), (3) insomnia, (4) fatigue, and (5) problems with concentration (unable to take in information when reading). These are experienced on most days and have been present for over two weeks (in her case since the birth three weeks ago). She was previously well, her bloods have been normal, and there is no indication of psychosis, bipolar disorder, or another psychiatric condition that could explain her symptoms. There is a clear impairment in her functioning and ability to care for her child. Hence, \u003Cstrong\u003Eperinatal depression\u003C/strong\u003E is the best explanation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBaby blues\u003C/strong\u003E is extremely common, affecting up to 80% of new mothers and has many overlapping features and symptoms. Baby blues usually develops in the first few days after birth, classically day 3, and resolves in less than 10 days. The table below describes key differences between baby blues and perinatal depression (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves emotional or behavioral symptoms in response to a stressor, but the symptoms are typically less severe and do not meet the criteria for a major depressive episode.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment insomnia\u003C/strong\u003E is a sleep disorder characterised by difficulty initiating or maintaining sleep that develops in response to an identifiable stressor (newborn baby). While this patient does have sleep disturbance, her presentation includes significant mood symptoms and functional impairment that extend beyond a primary sleep disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic fatigue syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves persistent fatigue not substantially alleviated by rest and not explained by another condition, but it does not account for the mood symptoms described here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Perinatal depression is characterised by persistent low mood, sleep disturbance, and fatigue lasting more than two weeks postpartum.","Baby blues typically resolves within 10 days of birth, while perinatal depression persists and significantly impacts functioning.","Screening for perinatal depression is essential as it requires appropriate treatment and support."],"references":["Ali E. Women\u0027s experiences with postpartum anxiety disorders: a narrative literature review. Int J Womens Health. 2018 May 29;10:237-249. doi: 10.2147/IJWH.S158621. PMID: 29881312; PMCID: PMC5983016. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5983016/","National Institute of mental health, 2019. Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder. [Internet]. Accessed on 13 Jan 2025. Available from:: https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/topics/post-traumatic-stress-disorder-ptsd","Royal College of Psychiatrists 2018. Postpartum psychosis. [Internet]. Accessed on 13 Jan 2025. Available from: https://www.rcpsych.ac.uk/mental-health/problems-disorders/postpartum-psychosis","Langan R, Goodbred AJ. Identification and Management of Peripartum Depression. Am Fam Physician. 2016 May 15;93(10):852-8. PMID: 27175720. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27175720/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97772"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2753"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17831"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17831"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4d21a9b7-4205-4472-affb-31bf6180a10e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4d21a9b7-4205-4472-affb-31bf6180a10e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":726,"height":162}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97772"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T11:05:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T11:13:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2753"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115769"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":